ğŸ”  First Unique Character in a String  

ğŸ“… Date: [07-1-2025]  
ğŸ–¥ï¸ Platform: [LeetCode/GFG]  
âš¡ Difficulty: [Easy]  

ğŸ” Problem Understanding  
ğŸ¯ Input: A string `s` containing lowercase English letters  
ğŸ¯ Output: Index of the first non-repeating character or `-1` if none exist  
ğŸ“ Constraints: `1 <= s.length <= 10^5`  
ğŸ”„ Edge cases: All characters repeat, single character string, first character is unique  

ğŸ’¡ Approach  
1ï¸âƒ£ Initial thoughts  
   ğŸ”¹ Use a frequency map to count occurrences  
   ğŸ”¹ Traverse again to find the first unique character  

2ï¸âƒ£ Optimal solution  
   ğŸ”¹ Use a 2D array `alpha[26][2]` to store:  
     â– `alpha[i][0]`: Frequency of character `i`  
     â– `alpha[i][1]`: First occurrence index of `i`  
   ğŸ”¹ Traverse `s` once to populate `alpha`  
   ğŸ”¹ Find the smallest index where frequency is `1`  

3ï¸âƒ£ Time/Space Complexity  
   â³ Time Complexity: `O(N)`, since we traverse the string twice  
   ğŸ’¾ Space Complexity: `O(1)`, since `alpha[26][2]` is constant  

ğŸ“ Pseudo Code  
ğŸ”¹ Initialize `alpha[26][2]` for storing frequency and index  
ğŸ”¹ Iterate over the string:  
   â– Update frequency and store first occurrence index  
ğŸ”¹ Find the smallest index with frequency 1  
ğŸ”¹ Return index or -1 if no unique character exists  

ğŸ’» Code  
```java
public int firstUniqChar(String s) {
    int alpha[][] = new int[26][2];
    int i = 0;
    for (char ch : s.toCharArray()) {
        alpha[ch - 'a'][0]++;
        if (alpha[ch - 'a'][0] == 1)
            alpha[ch - 'a'][1] = i;
        i++;
    }
    int min = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
    for (int k = 0; k < 26; k++) {
        if (alpha[k][0] == 1) {
            min = Math.min(alpha[k][1], min);
        }
    }
    return min == Integer.MAX_VALUE ? -1 : min;
}
```

